<ol class="blogroll wp-dark-mode-bg-image">
<li class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><span class="heap-of-link_name wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><a id="link-53863" class="track_this_link wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="https://philosophyofbrains.com/category/books/peter-carruthers-explaining-our-actions" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">“The methods still employed by many philosophers who address metaphysical questions about the mind and its contents… are bankrupt”</a></span> <span class="heap-of-link_description wp-dark-mode-bg-image">&#8212; Peter Carruthers discusses his new book, &#8220;Explaining Our Actions,&#8221; in a series of posts at the Brains Blog</span></li>
<li class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><span class="heap-of-link_name wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><a id="link-53862" class="track_this_link wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="https://unherd.com/2025/05/can-china-rescue-the-classics/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">“The enthusiasm of that country’s intellectual and political leaders for the study of Europe’s ancient world seems to grow by the month”</a></span> <span class="heap-of-link_description wp-dark-mode-bg-image">&#8212; on the increased interest in ancient Greek philosophy in China</span></li>
<li class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><span class="heap-of-link_name wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><a id="link-53861" class="track_this_link wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="https://handlingideas.blog/2025/05/14/thou-shalt-not-read-sloppily-on-your-phone-the-ethics-of-reading-1/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">“We can sense that this student ‘didn’t do the reading’, but we let them get away with it – just this once – because it’s the discussion we care about most for the moment”</a></span> <span class="heap-of-link_description wp-dark-mode-bg-image">&#8212; Martin Lenz begins a series of posts on different kinds of readers of philosophy and what can be learned from them</span></li>
<li class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><span class="heap-of-link_name wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><a id="link-53857" class="track_this_link wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2025/05/14/opinion/yale-canada-fascism.html?smid=nytcore-ios-share&amp;referringSource=articleShare" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">“We study fascism, and we’re leaving the US”</a></span> <span class="heap-of-link_description wp-dark-mode-bg-image">&#8212; a NYT video feature on Jason Stanley, Marci Shore, and Timothy Snyder, who are leaving Yale for Toronto</span></li>
<li class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><span class="heap-of-link_name wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><a id="link-53851" class="track_this_link wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="https://rudolphina.univie.ac.at/en/how-history-of-philosophy-can-help-us-in-times-of-extreme-suffering" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">“There is space between the position that ‘we can’t make sense of what it means for something to be absolute’ and the statement that ‘all positions are equally valid&#8217;”</a></span> <span class="heap-of-link_description wp-dark-mode-bg-image">&#8212; Martin Kusch is profiled by Lynn Chiu as he visits personally significant spots around Vienna on the eve of his retirement lecture</span></li>
<li class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><span class="heap-of-link_name wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><a id="link-53843" class="track_this_link wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="https://hiphination.substack.com/p/is-having-children-a-moral-issue?" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">What if procreative choices are a fixed point on which other moral reasons revolve, but are not themselves moral choices?”</a></span> <span class="heap-of-link_description wp-dark-mode-bg-image">&#8212; Barry Lam defends the “normie” view about procreation: generally, whatever you decide is ok</span></li>
<li class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><span class="heap-of-link_name wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><a id="link-53813" class="track_this_link wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="https://blog.apaonline.org/2025/05/13/2019-central-division-dewey-lecture-academic-philosophy-what-is-it-what-do-we-want-it-to-be/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">“Working as an American philosopher has turned out to be much more of an adventure than I ever could have anticipated”</a></span> <span class="heap-of-link_description wp-dark-mode-bg-image">&#8212; Alison Jaggar&#8217;s 2019 Dewey Lecture</span></li>
</ol>
<p>Mini-Heap posts usually appear when 7 or so new items accumulate in the <a class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="https://dailynous.com/heap-of-links/">Heap of Links</a>, a collection of items from around the web that may be of interest to philosophers. The Heap of Links consists partly of suggestions from readers; if you find something online that you think would be of interest to the philosophical community, please <a class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="mailto:dailynouseditor@gmail.com">send it in</a> for consideration for the Heap. Thank you.<br class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image" /><em class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><a class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="https://dailynous.com/2025/05/12/mini-heap-657/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Previous Edition</a> </em></p>
